\begin_layout Title
Some remarks about the agreement coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Jonas Moss 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
orcid{0000-0002-6876-6964}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Department of Data Science and Analytics
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

BI Norwegian Business School
\emph on

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

jonas.moss@bi.no
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The measure of agreement called 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

, originally developed to handle agreement data with high agreement, is
 growing in popularity.
 Our main goal with this paper is to question the motivation and utility
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and propose to use knowledge coefficients in its favour, but we will also
 demonstrate that the weighted variant of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

, called 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{2}$
\end_inset

, is incorrectly defined, and provide an alternative.
 More constructively, we provide a new estimator of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 which is consistent, where Gwet's estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is merely an approximation.
 Finally, we will generalize the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 to different classes of guessing models.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient is developed in the setting of an implicit guessing model,
 but is not a knowing coefficient.
 In the section on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 we discuss how to generalize it to different settings and how to estimate
 it and do inference under these settings.
 Moreover, we provide the first consistent estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

, as the current estimator 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gwet2008-qk,Gwet2014-iu"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is an approximation.
 In an attempt to interpret the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient, we find it is improperly justified, and strongly discourage
 its use.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Guessing model and knowledge coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
guessing model
\emph default
 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(x\mid i,j,s,x^{\star})=s_{ij}1[x=x_{i}^{\star}]+(1-s_{ij})q_{j}(x),\label{eq:full guessing model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea behind the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

 is to use a definition of chance agreement that differs from the classics,
 the Fleiss-type and the Cohen-type.
 When we assume a guessing model, we can rigorously define the notion of
 
\emph on
agreement due to guessing.
 
\emph default
Two raters 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{2}$
\end_inset

 may agree because they both happened to guess correctly, one of them happened
 to guess correctly and the other knew the correct classification, or because
 both know the correct classification.
 Since the probability that both know the correct classification is 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=\binom{J}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j_{1}>j_{2}}E[s_{ij_{1}}s_{ij_{2}}]$
\end_inset

, the weighted agreement to guessing can be defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{wg}=p_{wa}-\nu.\label{eq:weighted agreement due to guessing}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then we can define the generalized 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma_{w}=\frac{p_{wa}-p_{wg}}{1-p_{wg}}=\frac{\nu}{1-p_{wa}+\nu},\label{eq:gamma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which agrees with definition the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Equation (17)"
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $J=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C=2$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 are the unit weights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Be aware that 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Chapter 4"
key "Gwet2014-iu"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 redefines the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma^{\star}=\frac{p_{a}-p_{e}^{\star}}{1-p_{e}^{\star}},\quad\textrm{where }p_{e}^{\star}=\frac{1}{C-1}\sum_{c=1}^{C}p(c)(1-p(c))=\frac{1-p_{wf}}{C-1},\label{eq:AC1 approximation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{wf}$
\end_inset

 is the Fleiss-type chance agreement with unit weights.
 Originally, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "eq. 22"
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 presented 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\star}$
\end_inset

 as an approximation to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gwet correct"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, (when 
\begin_inset Formula $J=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C=2$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 are the unit weights), not the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient itself.
 In this paper we will understand 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gwet correct"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as the population 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient, not the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 We do not see any good reasons for using this approximation, as it is just
 as easy to use the original definition.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2014-iu"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proposed a weighted variant of his redefined 
\begin_inset Formula $\ac$
\end_inset

, christened the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{2}$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{p_{a}(w)-p_{e}^{\star}(w)}{1-p_{e}^{\star}(w)},\quad\textrm{where }p_{e}^{\star}(w)=\frac{1-p_{1f}}{C-1}\frac{\sum_{x,y}w(x,y)}{C}.
\]

\end_inset

The motivation behind 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}^{\star}(w)$
\end_inset

 is hard to follow, possibly because it is based directly on the approximation
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 instead of the correct 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Duality with chance disagreement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The motivation for the chance-corrected measure of agreement 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{wa}-p_{wc})/(1-p_{wc})$
\end_inset

 is most easily stated in terms of 
\emph on
disagreement
\emph default
.
 When 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-\frac{p_{wd}}{p_{wgd}}=\frac{p_{cd}-p_{d}}{p_{cd}}
\]

\end_inset

The denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p_{wg}$
\end_inset

 equals 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{wgd}$
\end_inset

, the probability of chance disagreement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is similar to the 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 from linear regression, which can be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R^{2}=1-\frac{\min_{\beta}E[(Y-\beta^{T}X)^{2}]}{\min_{\mu}E[(Y-\mu)^{2}]}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

