\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dp_{wa}}\frac{\nu}{(1-p_{wa})+\nu}=\frac{\nu}{[(1-p_{wa})+\nu]}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The knowledge coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He is working in the context of chance-corrected measures of agreement,
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p_{a}-p_{ca}}{1-p_{ca}},\label{eq:chance-corrected measure of agreement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the percent agreement among the raters and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ca}$
\end_inset

 is some notion of chance agreement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "p. 35"
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 develops the 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ac}$
\end_inset

, in the context of two raters and two items.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
(a) Chance agreement occurs when at least one rater rates an individual
 randomly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
(b) Only an unknown portion of the observed ratings is subject to randomness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Condition (a) implies a model for the ratings that allows us to classify
 a rating as either random of certain, an assumption that immediately brings
 us the guessing models discussed in the previous section.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x\mid i,j,s,x^{\star})=s_{ij}1[x=x_{i}^{\star}]+(1-s_{ij})q_{j}(x),
\]

\end_inset

Moreover, he makes the assumption that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

[...] random rating would normally lead to the classification of an individual
 into either category with the same probability 1/2.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "p. 37"
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Equation (17)"
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 defines the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\frac{p_{a}-p_{e}}{1-p_{e}}.\label{eq:Gwet correct}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of chance agreement, defined in ....
 The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of agreement due to chance in a particular sense, namely
 that the raters agree but at least of one of them is correct due to guessing.
 In the context of the guessing model, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

 is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{e}=p_{a}-\binom{J}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j>j'}E[s_{ij}s_{ij'}]=p_{a}-\nu.\label{eq:pe}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

 depends on knowing the skill parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{j}$
\end_inset

, it only makes sense only in a guessing model.
 From the definitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}$
\end_inset

, it follows that the numerator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}-p_{e}=\binom{J}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j>j'}s_{j}s_{j'}=\nu$
\end_inset

, the skill coefficient.
 Thus the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient may be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\frac{\nu}{1-p_{e}}=\frac{\nu}{1-p_{a}+\nu}.\label{eq:ac1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient is estimable if the knowledge coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 and the percent agreement 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

 is.
 The denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p_{e}$
\end_inset

 has, as far as I can see, never been properly motivated, neither by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Chapter 4"
key "Gwet2014-iu"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Gwet's explanations of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 match the knowledge coefficient far better, with the details narrowing
 it down to the Perrault–Leigh model, and the most appropriate coefficient
 for those persuaded by Gwet's arguments is the Brennan–Prediger coefficient.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An intuitive estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the plug-in estimator 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\gamma}=\frac{\hat{p}_{ga}^{-1}\hat{p}_{a}-1}{\hat{p}_{ga}^{-1}-2+\hat{p}_{a}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the empirical agreement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sample
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 has simple asymptotics under the Brennan–Prediger model.
 Using the delta method, we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}(\hat{\gamma}-\gamma)$
\end_inset

 converges in distribution to a normal with standard deviation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sd(\gamma)=\sqrt{p_{2a}-p_{a}^{2}}\frac{(C-1)^{2}}{(C+p_{a}-2)^{2}}.\label{eq:AC1 plugin standard deviation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use this expression to construct approximate confidence intervals.
 It is possible, but rare, even for small 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, to get 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{p}_{2a}<\hat{p}_{a}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we will use 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1$
\end_inset

 as an estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2a}-p_{a}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gwet's estimator of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsc{AC}_{1}$
\end_inset

 coefficient is the plugin estimator based on the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\star}=(p_{a}-p_{e}^{\star})/(1-p_{e}^{\star})$
\end_inset

 of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AC1 approximation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{e}^{\star} & = & (C-1)^{-1}\sum_{x=1}^{C}p(x)(1-p(x))=\frac{1-p_{ca}}{C-1}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The correct is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{e}=\frac{1-p_{a}}{C-1}$
\end_inset

, however.
 This estimator is almost always inconsistent, even under the BP model,
 but the bias is quite small.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:coverage ac1"

\end_inset

An illustration 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume the BP model, i.e.
 a guessing model where the guessing distribution is uniform.
 We will compare the coverage of normal theory confidence interval derived
 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AC1 plugin standard deviation-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, using the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

-distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom and , to the confidence interval described by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gwet2008-qk"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The true distribution of ratings is fixed at 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.1,0.05,0.65,0.1,0.2)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

